309.5.  That has nothing to do with spending power... it's a DIRECT indication of how much effort they have put into the guild. The whole premise of our DKP system is to make sure that if you attend raids, night after night, you will get the loot you want.  An auction at lottos defeats that.  The ppl that are up in the 300's of DKP earned have been around since the beginning of AL... and they got that high because of continuted dedication to the guild for over 18 months, and have not slacked off.  You are right in saying that Thott's 30 DKP is &quot;worth&quot; no more than the 1st 30 DKP a new member earns.  What is different however, is that Thott (or anything else for that matter with high total earned raid DKP) continues to prove they deserves loot 1st.  You can view DKP as a seniority system in some regards I suppose... except you only keep your seniorty by actively participating.  You cannot slack off and expect to keep looting the items you want before everyone else... because the numbers will show the truth.  <br>
<br>
The main problem with allowing discretionary DKP spending on an item is that DKP, while it displays some economic trends, is not based on capitalism.  We don't WANT someone to be able to earn 30 DKP their 1st month with the guild (as a side note, I think hobben said that 96 DKP could be earned in the month of April by attending everything) and then, just because they REALLY want an item, go overboard and spend a ton on it...which drives up the price and forces the person who deserves it to spend more.  It just doesn't jive with how we want to see our loot distributed... that person doesn't deserve xyz brand-new uber item over Thott, Hobben, or anyone else who has been putting in just as much effort for the same 30 points they just earned.  History matters... you put in a ton of time with AL... and you deserve certain items before other ppl who came after you.  This is quantitatively shown by DKP.  Allowing auctions can defeat this principle.  Of course, those who spend their DKP on twinks become exceptions to this rule... because although they may have learned a lot of DKP, their total DKP available for spending doesn't necessarily afford them the luxury of taking items 1st.  <br>
<br>
All this doesn't mean an auction system wouldn't work for other guilds... it just means it will never be implemented in our own system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ucelandrospellsongtriton.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Celandro Spellsong     Triton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/2/01 5:29:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=891.topic&index=82>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: DKNY</span><hr size=1> Like I said its your system you can do whatever the hell you want <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
Your system is certainly not a pure capitalist system, I am merely arguing it would be more fair to everyone in the guild if it were that way. I am a very hard core capitalist and I love economic systems and they all have their strengths and weaknesses. <br>
<br>
A few systems (these are merely sample implementations, there are other equally &quot;fair&quot;):<br>
<br>
Pure socialism -  There would be a queue for items and each item would go to whoever is next in the queue, then that person would go to the bottom of the list.  Every person in the guild would get the same number of items and is fair in that respect. Every member of the guild is seen as equally valuable and deserving of loot.  Differences between different members participation are not taken into account.<br>
<br>
Pure capitalism - Basically what I advocate. Give points to all raid attenders based on time spent (1 hour = 1 point), possible bonuses for special efforts (coming up with a new strategy, etc). When items drop they are sold to the highest bidder.  Every hour a member spends is seen as equally valuable.  Items can be sold back to the guild for points, points lended to friends, points pooled among friends. Long term participation in the system is not taken into account other than the fact that long term members have had more time to allow points to accrue.<br>
<br>
Monarchy - *cough cough Harmonium*. Guild leader decides who gets each item when it drops. Guild leader gets first drops in all cases, then guild leaders friends, etc. Fair because the monarch is the person who keeps the guild together, leads the guild, etc. Without the monarch there would be no guild in the first place.<br>
<br>
Oligarchy - Same as monarchy but with the guild officers all equal, and non officers not equal.<br>
<br>
DKP - This is a form of oligarchy. Basically the larger the difference between what you put into the guild and what you take from the guild, the higher your rank in the guild. You gain rank when an item that someone else gets drops, you lose rank when you get an item. Highest rank who wants the item, gets the item when it drops. In order to keep at the highest ranks, you must obtain points faster than you use them. Hoarding of points is encouraged and the obtaining of middle end items is severely discouraged.  For best results in this system, put lots into the guild at the very start and take no loot no matter how good. Once you are on top, keep yourself there by only obtaining the very best items. Fair because those who have put the most into the guild for the least return have first dibs on items when they drop.<br>
<br>
Chaos: /random 1 1000. No overhead! Screw systems! People roll on items they would use. All non-no drop items go back to the guild upon winning of a new item. Long term is fair as everyone gets their items and the speed of item obtaining is proportional to time spent raiding. Does not take into account that some classes have more competition for items/less items that benifit them/etc. <br>
<br>
Anyhow this post could be a lot longer.. perhaps I will post again. Pros and cons of each method I leave as an exercise to the reader. Note that all methods are &quot;fair&quot; depending on your definition of the word. Does fair mean that all members get the same number of items over time? That they get the same number of items over time spent? That those who have been most dedicated to the guild get their pick of items? That noone has to waste time keeping up to date a stupid system? That essential classes get the best items since they affect overall guild power most?<br>
